celled before being laid down.</ref>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* (No.104)/[[Japanese destroyer Akizuki (1941)|''Akizuki'']] (2 July 1941)\n* (No.105)/[[Japanese destroyer Teruzuki (1941)|''Teruzuki'']] (21 November 1941)\n* (No.106)/[[Japanese destroyer Suzutsuki (1942)|''Suzutsuki'']] (4 March 1942)\n* (No.107)/[[Japanese destroyer Hatsuzuki|''Hatsuzuki'']] (3 April 1942)\n* (No.108)/[[Japanese destroyer Niizuki|''Niizuki'']] (29 June 1942)\n* (No.109)/[[Japanese destroyer Wakatsuki|''Wakatsuki'']] (24 November 1942)\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Japanese destroyer Shimotsuki|''Shimotsuki'']] (7 April 1943)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Fuyutsuki|''Fuyutsuki'']] (20 January 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Harutsuki|''Harutsuki'']] (3 August 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Yoizuki|''Yoizuki'']] (25 September 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Natsuzuki|''Natsuzuki'']] (2 December 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Hanatsuki|''Hanatsuki'']] (10 October 1944)\n{{col-end}}\n\n===={{sclass-|Y\u016bgumo|destroyer|4}} (Type A) \u2014 19 ships====\nThe total of 19 excludes 8 cancelled.<ref>Cancelled ships were 8 from 1941 Programme (#348 to #355). These would have been named ''Kiyokaze'', ''Murakaze'', ''Satokaze'', ''Taekaze'', ''Kawagiri'', ''Tanigiri'', ''Umagiri'' and ''Yamagiri''. The Modified 5th Naval Armaments Supplement Programme included another 8 Type A ships of a slightly improved design (#5041 to #5048) but these were all cancelled before being laid down.</ref>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* (No.110)/[[Japanese destroyer Yugumo (1941)|''Yugumo'']] (16 March 1941)\n* (No.111)/[[Japanese destroyer Makigumo (1941)|''Makigumo'']] (5 November 1941)\n* (No.112)/[[Japanese destroyer Kazagumo|''Kazagumo'']] (26 September 1941)\n* (No.113)/[[Japanese destroyer Naganami|''Naganami'']] (5 March 1942)\n* (No.114)/[[Japanese destroyer Makinami|''Makinami'']] (17 December 1941)\n* (No.115)/[[Japanese destroyer Takanami|''Takanami'']] (16 March 1942)\n* (No.116)/[[Japanese destroyer \u014cnami|''\u014cnami'']] (11 August 1942)\n* (No.117)/[[Japanese destroyer Kiyonami|''Kiyonami'']] (17 August 1942)\n* (No.118)/[[Japanese destroyer Tamanami|''Tamanami'']] (20 December 1942)\n{{col-2}}\n* (No.120)/[[Japanese destroyer Suzunami|''Suzunami'']] (12 March 1943)\n* (No.121)/[[Japanese destroyer Fujinami|''Fujinami'']] (20 April 1943)\n* (No.122)/[[Japanese destroyer Hayanami|''Hayanami'']] (19 December 1942)\n* (No.123)/[[Japanese destroyer Hamanami|''Hamanami'']] (18 April 1943)\n* (No.124)/[[Japanese destroyer Okinami|''Okinami'']] (18 July 1943)\n* (No.125)/[[Japanese destroyer Kishinami|''Kishinami'']] (19 August 1943)\n* (No.126)/[[Japanese destroyer Asashimo|''Asashimo'']] (18 July 1943)\n* (No.127)/[[Japanese destroyer Hayashimo|''Hayashimo'']] (November 1943)\n* (No.128)/[[Japanese destroyer Akishimo|''Akishimo'']] (5 December 1943)\n* (No.129)/[[Japanese destroyer Kiyoshimo|''Kiyoshimo'']] (29 February 1944)\n{{col-end}}\n====[[Japanese destroyer Shimakaze (1942)|''Shimakaze'' class]] (Type C) \u2014 1 ship==== \nThe total excludes 16 cancelled.<ref>The 16 units were ordered as #733-#748 under the 1942 Programme but were cancelled without being laid down.</ref>\n* (No.119)/[[Japanese destroyer Shimakaze (1942)|''Shimakaze'']] (18 July 1742)\n===={{sclass-|Matsu|destroyer|4}} \u2014 18 ships====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Japanese destroyer Matsu (1944)|''Matsu'']] (3 February 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Take (1944)|''Take'']] (28 March 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Ume (1944)|''Ume'']] (24 April 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Momo (1944)|''Momo'']] (25 March 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Kuwa (1944)|''Kuwa'']] (25 May 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Kiri (1944)|''Kiri'']] (27 May 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Sugi (1944)|''Sugi'']] (3 July 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Maki (1944)|''Maki'']] (10 June 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Momi (1944)|''Momi'']] (16 June 1944)\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Japanese destroyer Kashi (1944)|''Kashi'']] (13 August 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroy