e'' (30 January 1987)\n{{col-end}}\n'''{{sclass-|Kong\u014d|destroyer|4}} (DDG) \u2014 4 ships'''\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* DDG-173 ''Kong\u014d'' (20 September 1991)\n* DDG-174 ''Kirishima'' (19 August 1993)\n{{col-2}}\n* DDG-175 ''My\u014dk\u014d'' (5 October 1994)\n* DDG-176 ''Ch\u014dkai'' (27 August 1996)\n{{col-end}}\n'''{{sclass-|Atago|destroyer|4}} (DDG) \u2014 2 ships'''\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* DDG-177 ''Atago'' (24 August 2005)\n{{col-2}}\n* DDG-178 ''Ashigara'' (30 August 2006)\n{{col-end}}\n'''{{sclass-|Maya|destroyer|4}} (DDG) \u2014 2 ships'''\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* DDG-179 ''Maya'' (30 July 2018)\n{{col-2}}\n* DDG-180 ''Hagura'' (17 July 2019)\n{{col-end}}\n\n=== Helicopter Destroyer ===\n\n'''{{sclass-|Haruna|destroyer|4}} (DDH) \u2014 2 ships'''\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* DDH-141 ''Haruna'' (1 February 1972)\n{{col-2}}\n* DDH-142 ''Hiei'' (13 August 1973)\n{{col-end}}\n'''{{sclass-|Shirane|destroyer|4}} (DDH) \u2014 2 ships'''\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* DDH-143 ''Shirane'' (18 September 1978)\n{{col-2}}\n* DDH-144 ''Kurama'' (20 September 1979)\n{{col-end}}\n'''{{sclass-|Hy\u016bga|helicopter destroyer|4}} (DDH) \u2014 2 ships'''\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* DDH-181 ''Hyuga'' (23 August 2007)\n{{col-2}}\n* DDH-182 ''Ise'' (21 August 2009)\n{{col-end}}\n'''{{sclass-|Izumo|helicopter destroyer|4}} (DDH) \u2014 2 ships'''\n\n(Re-designated as multi-purpose operation destroyer)'''<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.asahi.com/ajw/articles/AJ201812060055.html|title=Japan avoids flak by refusing to call flattop 'aircraft carrier'|date=6 December 2018|work=The Asahi Shimbun|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209044233/http://www.asahi.com/ajw/articles/AJ201812060055.html|archivedate=9 December 2018|accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref>'''\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* DDH-183 ''Izumo'' (6 August 2013)\n{{col-2}}\n* DDH-184 ''Kaga'' (27 August 2015)\n{{col-end}}\n\n=== Escort Destroyer ===\n'''[[Matsu-class destroyer|''Tachibana'' class]]  \u2014 1 ship'''\n*DE-261 ''[[JDS Wakaba|Wakaba]]'' (formerly IJN destroyer ''Nashi'')\n'''{{sclass-|Cannon|destroyer escort|4}} (DE) \u2014 2 ships transferred 1955 from USA'''\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* DE-262 ''Asahi'' (ex USS ''Amick'' - launch 27 May 1943)\n{{col-2}}\n* DE-263 ''Hatsuhi'' (ex USS ''Atherton'' - launch 27 May 1943)\n{{col-end}}\n'''{{JDS|Akebono|DE-201|6}} (DE) - 1 ship'''\n\n* DE-201 ''Akebono'' (30 October 1955)\n'''{{sclass-|Ikazuchi|destroyer escort|4}} (DE) \u2014 2 ships'''\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* DE-202 ''Ikazuchi'' (6 September 1955)\n{{col-2}}\n* DE-203 ''Inazuma'' (4 August 1955)\n{{col-end}}\n'''{{sclass-|Isuzu|destroyer escort|4}} (DE)\u2014 4 ships'''\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* DE-211 ''Isuzu'' (17 January 1961)\n* DE-212 ''Mogami'' (7 March 1961)\n{{col-2}}\n* DE-213 ''Kitakami'' (21 June 1963)\n* DE-214 ''\u014ci'' (15 June 1963)\n{{col-end}}\n'''{{sclass-|Chikugo|destroyer escort|4}} (DE)\u2014 11 ships'''\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* DE-215 ''Chikugo'' (13 January 1970)\n* DE-216 ''Ayase'' (16 September 1970)\n* DE-217 ''Mikuma'' (16 February 1971)\n* DE-218 ''Tokashi'' (25 November 1971)\n* DE-219 ''Iwase'' (29 June 1972)\n* DE-220 ''Chitose'' (25 January 1973)\n{{col-2}}\n* DE-221 ''Noyodo'' (28 August 1973)\n* DE-222 ''Teshio'' (29 May 1974)\n* DE-223 ''Yoshino'' (22 August 1974)\n* DE-224 ''Kumano'' (24 February 1975)\n* DE-225 ''Noshiro'' (23 December 1976)\n{{col-end}}\n'''{{JDS|Ishikari|DE-226|6}} (DE) - 1 ship'''\n\n* DE-226 ''Ishikari'' (18 March 1980)\n'''{{sclass-|Yubari|destroyer escort|4}} (DE)\u2014 2 ships'''\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* DE-227 ''Y\u016bbari'' (22 February 1982)\n{{col-2}}\n* DE-228 ''Y\u016bbetsu'' (25 January 1983)\n{{col-end}}\n'''{{sclass-|Abukuma|destroyer escort|4}} (DE)\u2014 6 ships'''\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* DE-229 ''Abukuma'' (21 December 1988)\n* DE-230 ''Jints\u016b'' (31 January 1989)\n* DE-231 ''\u014cyodo'' (19 December 1989)\n{{col-2}}\n* DE-232 ''Sendai'' (26 January 1990)\n* DE-233 ''Chikuma'' (25 January 1992)\n* DE-234 ''Tone'' (6 December 1991)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*Jentschura, Hansgeorg & Jung, Dieter & Mickel, Peter. ''Warships of the Imperial Japanese Navy, 1869-1945''. Arms & Armour Press, 1977. {{ISBN|1-85409-525-0}}.\n*Stille, Mark. ''Imperial Japanese Navy Destroyers 1919-45 (1) - Minekaze to Shiratsuyu Classes''. Osprey Publishing (No. 198), 2013. {{ISBN|978-1-84908-984-5}}\n*Stille, Mark. ''Imperial Japanese Navy Destroyers 1919-45 (2) - Asashio to Tachibana Classes''. Osprey Publishing (No. 202), 2013. {{ISBN|978-1-84908-987-6}}\n*Stille, Mark. ''Imperial Japanese Navy Antisubmarine Escorts 1941-45''. Osprey Publishing (No. 248), 2017. {{ISBN|978-1-4728-1816-4}}\n*Watts, Anthony J. ''Japanese Warships of World War II''. Ian Allan Ltd, London, 1966.\n*Whitley, M. J. ''Destroyers of World War Two: An International Encyclopedia''. Arms & Armour Press, 2000. {{ISBN|1-85409-521-8}}.\n\n{{Lists of Japanese ships}}\n[[Category:Destroyers of Japan]]\n[[Category:Lists of destroyers|Japan]]\n[[Category:Lists of ships of Japan|Destroyer]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThe following is a '''list of [[destroyer]]s and 1st class (steam) torpedo boats of [[Japan]]''' grouped by class or design. Each ship's name is followed by its launch date in brackets. In naval terminology, a destroyer is a fast and maneuverable yet long-endurance warship intended to escort larger vessels in a fleet, convoy or battle group and defend them against smaller, powerful, short-range attackers. The Japanese torpedo boat<ref>Jentschura p. 132 (''Akatsuki'' built by Yarrow & Co. in 1902; 224' long, displaced 415 tons, two 18\" Torpedoes, two 3\" guns, four 57mm Quick Firing Guns, complement 60 officers/men. Sunk by mine at Port Arthur on 17 May 1904)</ref> {{ship|Japanese torpedo boat|Kotaka||2}} of 1885 was \"the forerunner of torpedo boat destroyers that appeared a decade later\".<ref>{{cite book |last=Evans and Peattie |first=David C. and Mark R. |title=''Kaigun: Strategy, Tactics, and Technology in the Imperial Japanese Navy, 1887\u20131941'' |year=1997 |publisher=[[Naval Institute Press]] |location=Annapolis, Maryland  |isbn=0-87021-192-7}}</ref> They were designed to Japanese specifications and ordered from the London [[Yarrow Shipbuilders|Yarrow]] shipyards in 1885. The Yarrow shipyards, builder of the parts for the ''Kotaka'', \"considered Japan to have effectively invented the destroyer\".<ref>{{cite book |last=Howe |first=Christopher |title=''The Origins of Japanese Trade Supremacy: Development and Technology in Asia from 1540 to the Pacific War'' |year=1996 |publisher=University of Chicago Press |location=Chicago, Illinois |isbn=0-226-35485-7}}</ref>\n\n== [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] ==\n\n===[[Russo-Japanese War]]===\nThese twenty-three 'turtle-back' destroyers, all authorised under the Ten Year Naval Expansion Programme of 1898, comprised six ''Ikazuchi'' class built by Yarrow<ref>Yarrow & Company, Poplar, London.</ref> and six ''Murakumo'' class built by [[John I. Thornycroft &  Company|Thornycroft]]<ref>John I. Thornycroft & Company, Chiswick, London.</ref> in the UK, each carrying 1 - 12pdr (aft) and 5 - 6pdr guns and 2 - 18in torpedo tubes, and followed by two larger ships from each of the same builders (the ''Shirakumo'' class from Thornycroft and the ''Akatsuki'' class from Yarrow), in which a second 12pdr replaced the foremost 6pdr, and finally by seven ''Harusame'' class built in Japan. All were later rated as 3rd Class destroyers (under 600 tons each). The Programme also included sixteen First Class torpedo boats, included below (47 smaller 2nd and 3rd Class boats from this Programme are not included)\n===={{sclass-|Murakumo|destroyer|4}} \u2014 6 ships====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Murakumo'' (16 November 1898)\n* ''Shinonome'' (14 December 1898)\n* ''Y\u016bgiri'' (26 January 1899)\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Shiranui'' (14 March 1899)\n* ''Kagero'' (23 August 1899)\n* ''Usugumo'' (16 October 1900)\n{{col-end}}\n===={{sclass-|Ikazuchi|destroyer|4}} \u2014 6 ships====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Ikazuchi'' (15 November 1898)\n* ''Inazuma'' (28 January 1899)\n* ''Akebono'' (25 April 1899)\n{{col-2|}}\n* ''Sazanami'' (8 August 1899)\n* ''Niji'' (22 June 1899)\n* ''Oboro'' (5 October 1899)\n{{col-end}}\n====[[Japanese torpedo boat Shirataka|''Shirataka'' class]] - 1 1st class torpedo boat====\n* ''Shirataka'' (10 June 1899)\n====[[Hayabusa-class torpedo boat|''Hayabusa'' class]] - 15 1st class torpedo boats====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Hayabusa'' (1899)\n* ''Kasasagi'' (1900)\n* ''Manazuru'' (1900)\n* ''Chidori'' (1901)\n* ''Aotaka'' (February 1903)\n* ''Kari'' (14 March 1903)\n* ''Hato'' (July 1903)\n* ''Tsubame'' (August 1903)\n{{col-2|}}\n* ''Hibari'' (October 1903)\n* ''Kiji'' (November 1903)\n* ''Hashitaka'' (December 1903)\n* ''Sahi'' (December 1903\n* ''Uzura'' (February 1904)\n* ''Kamone'' (April 1904)\n* ''\u014ctori'' (April 1904)\n{{col-end}}\n===={{sclass-|Shirakumo|destroyer|4}} \u2014 2 ships====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Shirakumo'' (1 October 1901)\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Asashio'' (10 January 1902)\n{{col-end}}\n====[[Akatsuki-class destroyer (1901)|''Akatsuki'' class]] \u2014 2 ships====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Akatsuki'' (13 November 1901)\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Kasumi'' (23 January 1902)\n{{col-end}}\n===={{sclass-|Harusame|destroyer|4}} \u2014 7 ships====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Harusame'' (31 October 1902)\n* ''Murasame'' (29 November 1902)\n* ''Hayatori'' (12 March 1903)\n* ''Asagiri'' (15 April 1903)\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Ariake'' (7 December 1904)\n* ''Fubuki'' (21 January 1905)\n* ''Arare'' (5 April 1905)\n{{col-end}}\n===[[World War I]]===\nBefore and during World War I, Japan established three grades of destroyers - the large (over 1,000 tons) 1st Class or ocean-going type, the medium (600 to 1,000 tons) 2nd Class type and the small (below 600 tons) 3rd Class type. Between 1904 and 1918, Japan built thirty-two 3rd Class destroyers (the ''Kamikaze'' class), twenty-two 2nd Class destroyers (the ''Sakura'', ''Kaba'', ''Momo'' and ''Enoki'' classes) and eight 1st Class destroyers (the ''Umikaze'', ''Isokaze'' and ''Kawakaze'' classes). They also purchased two further 1st Class destroyers (the ''Urakaze'' class) built in the UK by Yarrow.\n====[[Kamikaze-class destroyer (1905)|''Kamikaze'' class]] \u2014 32 ships====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Kamikaze'' (15 July 1905)\n* ''Hatsushimo'' (13 May 1905)\n* ''Yayoi'' (7 August 1905)\n* ''Kisaragi'' (19 October 1905)\n* ''Asakaze'' (28 October 1905)\n* ''Shiratsuyu'' (12 February 1906)\n* ''Shirayuki'' (12 October 1906)\n* ''Matsukaze'' (23 December 1906)\n* ''Harukaze'' (25 December 1905)\n* ''Shigure'' (12 March 1906)\n* ''Asatsuyu'' (2 April 1906)\n* ''Hayate'' (22 May 1906)\n* ''Oite'' (10 January 1906)\n* ''Y\u016bnagi'' (22  August 1906)\n* ''Y\u016bgure'' (17 November 1905)\n* ''Y\u016bdachi'' (26 March 1906)\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Mikazuki'' (26 May 1906)\n* ''Nowaki'' (25 July 1906)\n* ''Ushio'' (30 August 1905)\n* ''Nenohi'' (30 August 1905)\n* ''Hibiki'' (31 March 1906)\n* ''Shirotae'' (30 July 1906)\n* ''Hatsuharu'' (21 May 1906)\n* ''Wakaba'' (25 November 1906)\n* ''Hatsuyuki'' (8 March 1906)\n* ''Uzuki'' (20 September 1906)\n* ''Minatsuki'' (5 November 1906)\n* ''Nagatsuki'' (15 December 1906)\n* ''Kikutsuki'' (10 April 1907)\n* ''Uranami'' (8 December 1907)\n* ''Isonami'' (21 November 1908)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Ayanami (1909)|''Ayanami'']] (20 March 1909)\n{{col-end}}\n===={{sclass-|Umikaze|destroyer|4}} \u2014 2 ships====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Umikaze'' (10 October 1910)\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Japanese destroyer Yamakaze (1911)|''Yamakaze'']] (21 January 1911)\n{{col-end}}\n===={{sclass-|Sakura|destroyer|4}} \u2014 2 ships====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Sakura'' (20 December 1911)\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Japanese destroyer Tachibana (1912)|''Tachibana'']] (27 January 1912)\n{{col-end}}\n===={{sclass-|Kaba|destroyer|4}} \u2014 10 ships====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Kaba'' (6 February 1915)\n* ''Kashiwa'' (14 February 1915)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Sakaki (1915)|''Sakaki'']] (4 March 1915)\n* ''Katsura'' (15 February 1915)\n* ''Sugi'' (16 February 1915)\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Kaede'' (20 February 1915)\n* ''Ume'' (27 February 1915)\n* ''Kiri'' (28 February 1915)\n* ''Kusunoki'' (5 March 1915)\n* ''Matsu'' (5 March 1915)\n{{col-end}}\n===={{sclass-|Urakaze|destroyer|4}} \u2014 2 ships====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Urakaze'' (16 February 1915)\n{{col-2}}\n*[[Italian destroyer Audace (1916)|''Kawakaze'']] (27 September 1915)<ref>sold to [[Kingdom of Italy (1861\u20131946)|Italy]] ten days after her launching as ''Audace''.</ref>\n{{col-end}}\n===={{sclass-|Momo|destroyer|4}} \u2014 4 ships====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Momo'' (12 October 1916)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Kashi (1916)|''Kashi'']] (1 December 1916)\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Hinoki'' (25 December 1916)\n* ''Yanagi'' (24 February 1917)\n{{col-end}}\n===={{sclass-|Isokaze|destroyer|4}} \u2014 4 ships====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Isokaze'' (5 October 1916)\n* ''Amatsukaze'' (5 October 1916)\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Hamakaze'' (30 October 1916)\n* ''Tokitsukaze'' (27 December 1917)\n{{col-end}}\n===={{sclass-|Acorn|destroyer|4}}/[[:ja:\u6a44\u6b16\u578b\u99c6\u9010\u8266|''Kanran'' class]] - 2 ships==== \n(both ships loaned from the [[Royal Navy]] from June 1917 to 1919)\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Kanran'' (ex HMS ''Nemesis'' - launched 9 August 1910)\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Sendan'' (ex HMS ''Minstrel'' - launched 2 February 1911)\n{{col-end}}\n===={{sclass-|Kawakaze|destroyer|4}} \u2014 2 ships====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Kawakaze'' (10 October 1917)<ref>a replacement for the ship of the same name sold to Italy.</ref>\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Tanikaze'' (20 July 1918)\n{{col-end}}\n===={{sclass-|Enoki|destroyer|4}} \u2014 6 ships====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Enoki'' (5 March 1918)\n* ''Maki'' (28 December 1917)\n* ''Nara'' (28 March 1918)\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Keyaki'' (15 January 1918)\n* ''Kuwa'' (23 February 1918)\n* ''Tsubaki'' (23 February 1918)\n{{col-end}}\n\n===The Inter-War Period===\nFrom 1919 onwards, a series of destroyers were built regularly in Japan. No further 3rd Class ships were built after 1909, and only two further classes of 2nd Class ships (the ''Momi'' and ''Wakatake'' classes) were built by 1923, after which all were 1st Class. The ships of the ''Wakatake'', ''Kamikaze'' and ''Mutsuki'' classes were initially given numbers rather than names, but names were assigned on 1 August 1928. The numbering system continued after 1928, but were not assigned to ships, which were all named.\n===={{sclass-|Momi|destroyer|4}} \u2014 21 ships==== \nThe total of 21 excludes 7 cancelled.\n({{ship|Japanese destroyer|Warabi|1921|2}} lost in August 1927; {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Momi|1919|2}}, {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Kaya|1919|2}} and {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Nashi|1919|2}} scrapped by 1940, leaving 17 which served in the [[Pacific War]])\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Japanese destroyer Momi (1919)|''Momi'']] (10 June 1919)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Kaya (1919)|''Kaya'']] (10 June 1919)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Nire (1919)|''Nire'']] (22 December 1919)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Kuri (1920)|''Kuri'']] (19 March 1920)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Nashi (1919)|''Nashi'']] (26 August 1919)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Take (1919)|''Take'']] (26 August 1919)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Kaki (1919)|''Kaki'']] (20 October 1919)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Tsuga (1920)|''Tsuga'']] (17 April 1920)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Kiku (1920)|''Kiku'']] (13 October 1920)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Aoi (1920)|''Aoi'']] (9 December 1920)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Hagi (1920)|''Hagi'']] (29 October 1920)\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Japanese destroyer Susuki (1921)|''Susuki'']] (21 February 1921)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Fuji (1920)|''Fuji'']] (27 November 1920)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Tsuta (1921)|''Tsuta'']] (9 May 1921)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Ashi (1921)|''Ashi'']] (3 September 1921)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Hishi (1921)|''Hishi'']] (9 May 1921)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Hasu (1921)|''Hasu'']] (8 December 1921)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Sumire (1921)|''Sumire'']] (14 December 1921)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Yomogi (1922)|''Yomogi'']] (14 March 1922)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Warabi (1921)|''Warabi'']] (28 September 1921)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Tade (1921)|''Tade'']] (15 March 1921)\n{{col-end}}\n===={{sclass-|Minekaze|destroyer|4}} \u2014 15 ships====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Japanese destroyer Minekaze|''Minekaze'']] (8 February 1919)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Sawakaze (1919)|''Sawakaze'']] (7 January 1919)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Okikaze|''Okikaze'']] (3 October 1919)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Shimakaze (1920)|''Shimakaze'']] (31 March 1920)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Nadakaze|''Nadakaze'']] (26 June 1920)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Yakaze|''Yakaze'']] (10 April 1920)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Hakaze|''Hakaze'']] (21 June 1920)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Shiokaze|''Shiokaze'']] (22 October 1920)\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Japanese destroyer Akikaze|''Akikaze'']] (14 December 1920)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Y\u016bkaze|''Y\u016bkaze'']] (28 April 1921)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Tachikaze|''Tachikaze'']] (31 March 1921)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Hokaze|''Hokaze'']] (12 July 1921)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Nokaze|''Nokaze'']] (1 October 1921)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Namikaze|''Namikaze'']] (24 June 1922)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Numakaze|''Numakaze'']] (22 May 1922)\n{{col-end}}\n===={{sclass-|Wakatake|destroyer|4}} \u2014 8 ships==== \nThe total of 8 excludes 5 cancelled in 1922.\n({{ship|Japanese destroyer|Sawarabi||2}} lost in December 1932; leaving 7 which served in the [[Pacific War]])\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* No.2/[[Japanese destroyer Wakatake (1922)|''Wakatake'']] (24 July 1922)\n* No.4/[[Japanese destroyer Kuretake (1922)|''Kuretake'']] (21 October 1922)\n* No.6/[[Japanese destroyer Sanae (1923)|''Sanae'']] (15 February 1923)\n* No.8/[[Japanese destroyer Sawarabi (1923)|''Sawarabi'']] (1 September 1923)\n* No.10/[[Japanese destroyer Asagao (1922)|''Asagao'']] (4 November 1922)\n* No.12/[[Japanese destroyer Y\u016bgao (1923)|''Y\u016bgao'']] (14 April 1923)\n* No.14/''Kijiko'' (cancelled 1922)\n{{col-2}}\n* No.16/[[Japanese destroyer Fuy\u014d (1922)|''Fuy\u014d'']] (22 September 1922)\n* No.18/[[Japanese destroyer Karukaya (1923)|''Karukaya'']] (19 March 1923)\n* No.20/''Omadaka'' (cancelled 1922)\n* No.22/''Nadeshiko'' (cancelled 1922)\n* No.24/''Botan'' (cancelled 1922)\n* No.26/''Basho'' (cancelled 1922)\n{{col-end}}\n====[[Kamikaze-class destroyer (1922)|''Kamikaze'' class]] \u2014 9 ships====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* No.1/[[Japanese destroyer Kamikaze (1922)|''Kamikaze'']] (25 September 1922)\n* No.3/[[Japanese destroyer Asakaze (1922)|''Asakaze'']] (8 December 1922)\n* No.5/[[Japanese destroyer Harukaze (1922)|''Harukaze'']] (18 December 1922)\n* No.7/[[Japanese destroyer Matsukaze (1923)|''Matsukaze'']] (30 October 1923)\n* No.9/[[Japanese destroyer Hatakaze (1924)|''Hatakaze'']] (15 March 1924)\n{{col-2}}\n* No.11/[[Japanese destroyer Oite (1924)|''Oite'']] (27 November 1924)\n* No.13/[[Japanese destroyer Hayate (1925)|''Hayate'']] (23 March 1925)\n* No.15/[[Japanese destroyer Asanagi|''Asanagi'']] (21 April 1924)\n* No.17/[[Japanese destroyer Y\u016bnagi (1924)|''Y\u016bnagi'']] (23 April 1924)\n{{col-end}}\n===={{sclass-|Mutsuki|destroyer|4}} \u2014 12 ships====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* No.19/[[Japanese destroyer Mutsuki|''Mutsuki'']] (23 July 1925)\n* No.21/[[Japanese destroyer Kisaragi (1925)|''Kisaragi'']] (5 June 1925)\n* No.23/[[Japanese destroyer Yayoi (1925)|''Yayoi'']] (11 July 1925)\n* No.25/[[Japanese destroyer Uzuki (1925)|''Uzuki'']] (15 October 1925)\n* No.27/[[Japanese destroyer Satsuki (1925)|''Satsuki'']] (25 March 1925)\n* No.28/[[Japanese destroyer Minazuki (1926)|''Minazuki'']] (25 May 1926)\