oats\". The total of 8 excludes another 8 cancelled units.<ref>The cancelled units, Torpedo boats #13 to #20 under the 1934 Programme, were projected to have been named ''Hatsutaka'', ''Aotaka'', ''Wakataka'', ''Kumataka'', ''Yamadori'', ''Mizudori'', ''Umidori'' and ''Komadori''; however, no contracts were placed by the time the order was changed in 1937 in favour of [[CH-4-class submarine chaser|Submarine chasers #4 to #11]].</ref>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Japanese torpedo boat \u014ctori (1935)|''\u014ctori'']] (25 April 1935)\n* [[Japanese torpedo boat Kasasagi (1935)|''Kasasagi'']] (28 October 1935)\n* [[Japanese torpedo boat Hiyodori|''Hiyodori'']] (25 October 1935)\n* [[Japanese torpedo boat Hayabusa (1935)|''Hayabusa'']] (28 October 1935)\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Japanese torpedo boat Hato (1937)|''Hato'']] (25 January 1937)\n* [[Japanese torpedo boat Sagi (1937)|''Sagi'']] (30 January 1937)\n* [[Japanese torpedo boat Kari (1937)|''Kari'']] (20 January 1937)\n* [[Japanese torpedo boat Kiji (1937)|''Kiji'']] (26 January 1937)\n{{col-end}}\n\n===={{sclass-|Shiratsuyu|destroyer|4}} \u2014 10 ships====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* (No.65)/[[Japanese destroyer Shiratsuyu (1935)|''Shiratsuyu'']] (5 April 1935)\n* (No.66)/[[Japanese destroyer Shigure (1935)|''Shigure'']] (18 May 1935)\n* (No.67)/[[Japanese destroyer Murasame (1935)|''Murasame'']] (20 June 1935) \n* (No.68)/[[Japanese destroyer Y\u016bdachi (1936)|''Y\u016bdachi'']] (21 June 1936)\n* (No.69)/[[Japanese destroyer Harusame (1935)|''Harusame'']] (21 September 1935)\n{{col-2}}\n* (No.70)/[[Japanese destroyer Samidare (1935)|''Samidare'']] (6 July 1935)\n* (No.71)/[[Japanese destroyer Umikaze (1936)|''Umikaze'']] (27 November 1936)\n* (No.72)/[[Japanese destroyer Yamakaze (1936)|''Yamakaze'']] (21 February 1936)\n* (No.73)/[[Japanese destroyer Kawakaze (1936)|''Kawakaze'']] (1 November 1936)\n* (No.74)/[[Japanese destroyer Suzukaze|''Suzukaze'']] (11 March 1937)\n{{col-end}}\n===={{sclass-|Asashio|destroyer|4}} \u2014 10 ships====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* (No.75)/[[Japanese destroyer Asashio (1936)|''Asashio'']] (16 December 1936)\n* (No.76)/[[Japanese destroyer \u014cshio|''\u014cshio'']] (19 April 1937)\n* (No.77)/[[Japanese destroyer Michishio|''Michishio'']] (15 March 1937)\n* (No.78)/[[Japanese destroyer Arashio|''Arashio'']] (26 May 1937)\n* (No.79)/[[Japanese destroyer Yamagumo (1937)|''Yamagumo'']] (24 July 1937)\n{{col-2}}\n* (No.80)/[[Japanese destroyer Natsugumo (1937)|''Natsugumo'']] (26 May 1937)\n* (No.81)/[[Japanese destroyer Asagumo (1937)|''Asagumo'']] (5 November 1937)\n* (No.82)/[[Japanese destroyer Minegumo (1937)|''Minegumo'']] (4 November 1937)\n* (No.83)/[[Japanese destroyer Arare (1937)|''Arare'']] (16 November 1937)\n* (No.84)/[[Japanese destroyer Kasumi (1937)|''Kasumi'']] (18 November 1937)\n{{col-end}}\n===={{sclass-|Kager\u014d|destroyer|4}} (Type A) \u2014 19 ships====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* (No.85)/[[Japanese destroyer Kager\u014d (1938)|''Kager\u014d'']] (27 September 1938)\n* (No.86)/[[Japanese destroyer Shiranui (1938)|''Shiranui'']] (28 June 1938)\n* (No.87)/[[Japanese destroyer Kuroshio (1938)|''Kuroshio'']] (25 October 1938)\n* (No.88)/[[Japanese destroyer Oyashio|''Oyashio'']] (29 November 1938)\n* (No.89)/[[Japanese destroyer Hayashio|''Hayashio'']] (19 April 1939)\n* (No.90)/[[Japanese destroyer Natsushio|''Natsushio'']] (23 February 1939)\n* (No.91)/[[Japanese destroyer Hatsukaze|''Hatsukaze'']] (24 January 1939)\n* (No.92)/[[Japanese destroyer Yukikaze (1939)|''Yukikaze'']] (24 March 1939)\n* (No.93)/[[Japanese destroyer Amatsukaze (1939)|''Amatsukaze'']] (19 October 1939)\n* (No.94)/[[Japanese destroyer Tokitsukaze (1939)|''Tokitsukaze'']] (10 November 1939)\n{{col-2}}\n* (No.95)/[[Japanese destroyer Urakaze (1940)|''Urakaze'']] (19 April 1940)\n* (No.96)/[[Japanese destroyer Isokaze (1939)|''Isokaze'']] (19 June 1939)\n* (No.97)/[[Japanese destroyer Hamakaze (1940)|''Hamakaze'']] (25 November 1940)\n* (No.98)/[[Japanese destroyer Tanikaze (1940)|''Tanikaze'']] (1 November 1940)\n* (No.99)/[[Japanese destroyer Nowaki (1940)|''Nowaki'']] (17 September 1940)\n* (No.100)/[[Japanese destroyer Arashi|''Arashi'']] (22 April 1940)\n* (No.101)/[[Japanese destroyer Hagikaze|''Hagikaze'']] (18 June 1940)\n* (No.102)/[[Japanese destroyer Maikaze|''Maikaze'']] (15 March 1941)\n* (No.103)/[[Japanese destroyer Akigumo (1941)|''Akigumo'']] (11 April 1941)\n{{col-end}}\n\n====[[Akizuki-class destroyer (1942)|''Akizuki'' class]] (Type B) \u2014 12 ships====\nThe total of 12  excludes 1 uncompleted (''Michitsuki'') and 3 cancelled; 21 intended further ships were never ordered.<ref>Cancelled ships were 3 from the 1941 Programme (#367 to #369), to have been named ''Kiyotsuki'', ''\u014ctsuki'' and ''Hazuki''. The 1942 Programme included another 16 Type B ships of an improved 2,933 ton design (#770 to #785) but this entire programme was cancelled; instead the Modified 5th Naval Armaments Supplement Programme included another 23 Type B ships of an even more improved 2,701 ton design (#5061 to #5083) but these were all cancelled before being laid down.</ref>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* (No.104)/[[Japanese destroyer Akizuki (1941)|''Akizuki'']] (2 July 1941)\n* (No.105)/[[Japanese destroyer Teruzuki (1941)|''Teruzuki'']] (21 November 1941)\n* (No.106)/[[Japanese destroyer Suzutsuki (1942)|''Suzutsuki'']] (4 March 1942)\n* (No.107)/[[Japanese destroyer Hatsuzuki|''Hatsuzuki'']] (3 April 1942)\n* (No.108)/[[Japanese destroyer Niizuki|''Niizuki'']] (29 June 1942)\n* (No.109)/[[Japanese destroyer Wakatsuki|''Wakatsuki'']] (24 November 1942)\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Japanese destroyer Shimotsuki|''Shimotsuki'']] (7 April 1943)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Fuyutsuki|''Fuyutsuki'']] (20 January 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Harutsuki|''Harutsuki'']] (3 August 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Yoizuki|''Yoizuki'']] (25 September 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Natsuzuki|''Natsuzuki'']] (2 December 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Hanatsuki|''Hanatsuki'']] (10 October 1944)\n{{col-end}}\n\n===={{sclass-|Y\u016bgumo|destroyer|4}} (Type A) \u2014 19 ships====\nThe total of 19 excludes 8 cancelled.<ref>Cancelled ships were 8 from 1941 Programme (#348 to #355). These would have been named ''Kiyokaze'', ''Murakaze'', ''Satokaze'', ''Taekaze'', ''Kawagiri'', ''Tanigiri'', ''Umagiri'' and ''Yamagiri''. The Modified 5th Naval Armaments Supplement Programme included another 8 Type A ships of a slightly improved design (#5041 to #5048) but these were all cancelled before being laid down.</ref>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* (No.110)/[[Japanese destroyer Yugumo (1941)|''Yugumo'']] (16 March 1941)\n* (No.111)/[[Japanese destroyer Makigumo (1941)|''Makigumo'']] (5 November 1941)\n* (No.112)/[[Japanese destroyer Kazagumo|''Kazagumo'']] (26 September 1941)\n* (No.113)/[[Japanese destroyer Naganami|''Naganami'']] (5 March 1942)\n* (No.114)/[[Japanese destroyer Makinami|''Makinami'']] (17 December 1941)\n* (No.115)/[[Japanese destroyer Takanami|''Takanami'']] (16 March 1942)\n* (No.116)/[[Japanese destroyer \u014cnami|''\u014cnami'']] (11 August 1942)\n* (No.117)/[[Japanese destroyer Kiyonami|''Kiyonami'']] (17 August 1942)\n* (No.118)/[[Japanese destroyer Tamanami|''Tamanami'']] (20 December 1942)\n{{col-2}}\n* (No.120)/[[Japanese destroyer Suzunami|''Suzunami'']] (12 March 1943)\n* (No.121)/[[Japanese destroyer Fujinami|''Fujinami'']] (20 April 1943)\n* (No.122)/[[Japanese destroyer Hayanami|''Hayanami'']] (19 December 1942)\n* (No.123)/[[Japanese destroyer Hamanami|''Hamanami'']] (18 April 1943)\n* (No.124)/[[Japanese destroyer Okinami|''Okinami'']] (18 July 1943)\n* (No.125)/[[Japanese destroyer Kishinami|''Kishinami'']] (19 August 1943)\n* (No.126)/[[Japanese destroyer Asashimo|''Asashimo'']] (18 July 1943)\n* (No.127)/[[Japanese destroyer Hayashimo|''Hayashimo'']] (November 1943)\n* (No.128)/[[Japanese destroyer Akishimo|''Akishimo'']] (5 December 1943)\n* (No.129)/[[Japanese destroyer Kiyoshimo|''Kiyoshimo'']] (29 February 1944)\n{{col-end}}\n====[[Japanese destroyer Shimakaze (1942)|''Shimakaze'' class]] (Type C) \u2014 1 ship==== \nThe total excludes 16 cancelled.<ref>The 16 units were ordered as #733-#748 under the 1942 Programme but were cancelled without being laid down.</ref>\n* (No.119)/[[Japanese destroyer Shimakaze (1942)|''Shimakaze'']] (18 July 1742)\n===={{sclass-|Matsu|destroyer|4}} \u2014 18 ships====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Japanese destroyer Matsu (1944)|''Matsu'']] (3 February 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Take (1944)|''Take'']] (28 March 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Ume (1944)|''Ume'']] (24 April 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Momo (1944)|''Momo'']] (25 March 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Kuwa (1944)|''Kuwa'']] (25 May 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Kiri (1944)|''Kiri'']] (27 May 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Sugi (1944)|''Sugi'']] (3 July 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Maki (1944)|''Maki'']] (10 June 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Momi (1944)|''Momi'']] (16 June 1944)\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Japanese destroyer Kashi (1944)|''Kashi'']] (13 August 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Kaya (1944)|''Kaya'']] (30 July 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Nara (1944)|''Nara'']] (12 October 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Sakura (1944)|''Sakura'']] (6 September 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Yanagi (1944)|''Yanagi'']] (25 November 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Tsubaki (1944)|''Tsubaki'']] (30 September 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Hinoki (1944)|''Hinoki'']] (4 July 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Kaede (1944)|''Kaede'']] (25 July 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Keyaki (1944)|''Keyaki'']] (30 September 1944)\n{{col-end}}\n===={{sclass-|Tachibana|destroyer|4}} (Modified ''Matsu'') \u2014 23 ships==== \nThe total includes 9 never completed but excludes cancelled units\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Japanese destroyer Kaki (1944)|''Kaki'']] (11 December 1944)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Kaba (1945)|''Kaba'']] (27 February 1945)\n* [[Japanese destroyer Tachibana (1944)|''Tachibana'']]